<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="325" type="collection and habitat data">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="325">Collection and habitat data.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="325">
This species has been collected from leaves and stems of pondweeds (
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Potamogetonaceae" genus="Potamogeton" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Potamogeton" order="Alismatales" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Potamogeton</taxonomicName>
sp.) (
<bibRefCitation author="Askevold, IS" journalOrPublisher="Transactions of the American Entomological Society" pageId="14" pageNumber="335" pagination="360 - 430" title="The genus Neohaemonia Szekessy in North America (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Donaciinae): systematics, reconstructed phylogeny, and geographic history." volume="113" year="1987">Askevold 1987</bibRefCitation>
) and probably has a similar biology as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Neohaemonia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Neohaemonia melsheimeri" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melsheimeri">Neohaemonia melsheimeri</taxonomicName>
. One adult from New Brunswick was swept from foliage along a lake margin during June.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
